OpenCL and CUDA are both parallel computing platforms for programming computer graphics and high-performance computing applications, but there are some key differences between the two.
OpenCL is an open standard developed by Khronos Group, an open consortium of computer hardware and software companies including AMD, Apple, Qualcomm, IBM, Intel, NVIDIA and others. It is designed to enable developers to write programs (called kernels) to be executed across a heterogeneous set of computing devices, including GPUs, CPUs, FPGAs and custom hardware. OpenCL is implemented and supported by hardware and software vendors, such as major graphics card manufacturers NVIDIA and AMD.

There are many ways to parallelize neural networks, but one popular technique is to use multi-GPU training. This involves training multiple GPUs in parallel, which can significantly speed up the training process. There are a few different ways to implement this, but one common approach is to use a multi-GPU version of an algorithm such as mini-batch Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) or mini-batch Adam. These algorithms divide the dataset into smaller batches and train each batch concurrently on a different GPU. This can dramatically reduce the total training time and improve the convergence rate. If you're using TensorFlow, for example, you can use the "distributed_batch_gather" function to implement this approach. You can also use multi-GPU training on the CPU if you don't have access to GPUs, but this will be less efficient than using GPUs unless the dataset is very large. Another common way to parallelize neural networks is to use clusterified training, which involves distributing the model across multiple machines and training on each machine in parallel.
